What is derived
---------------
Historically, the CTLL compile-time LL(1) parser (ctll::fixed_string
and supporting headers) was consumed via the compile-time-lark
submodule; it descended from Hana Dusikova's CTRE via notre. As of
2026-07 no CTLL code ships in this tree - the NTTP string carrier is
ctc::string from compile-time-containers (MIT) - but the repository's
git history contains CTLL, and this notice preserves the lineage.
This repository began as a clone of its sibling compile-time-html
(https://github.com/alexios-angel/compile-time-html) - itself a clone
of compile-time-xml - and keeps that git history; the build and
packaging scaffolding follows the sibling projects compile-time-json
and compile-time-json5 (https://github.com/alexios-angel/). The
constexpr JavaScript parser, the runtime value model and interpreter,
and the ctjs API are original to this repository.

Attribution for the historical CTLL engine belongs to Hana Dusikova;
this file preserves it as required by Section 4(c) of the Apache
License 2.0 for the versions that shipped it.

compile-time-containers (https://github.com/alexios-angel/
compile-time-containers, MIT) is the sole submodule under external/:
ctc::string carries NTTP scripts and ctc::cfunction (which began life
in this repository) type-erases native functions.

The JavaScript language semantics implemented here follow ECMA-262
(the ECMAScript Language Specification, Ecma International).
